post_text:
Post 2 of 3: The attached documents show the Coffeyville Public Schools mill rate over time as compared to other local entities. Over the last 10 years the mill rate for the school district has actually decreased by 1.9%.
The second document shows the current mill rate for Coffeyville Public Schools compared to other area SEK school districts. Our district has the lowest mill rate of all districts. The proposed budget for the coming school year increases the mill rate by 1, this would keep us next to the lowest mill rate in the region provided no one else moves up. Our mill rate would still be lower than it was 10 years ago. This 1 mill increase will cost most households in Coffeyville less than $12 a year while providing much needed upgrades and additions to our oldest buildings.

post_text: Post 1 of 3: Recently there have been some misinformed newspaper ads and misinformation circulating. The ads focus on the districtâ€™s plan to build a new gym. Please check out the August 13th edition of the Montgomery County Chronicle for accurate information from the board meeting held August 10th. There IS a gym included in the plan, but there is SO much more! Our board of education has been working diligently for several months to approve a plan that addresses the needs of our students while remaining mindful of the impact on our community. The gym will be used daily by Roosevelt Middle School students for Physical Education and will be used by both middle and high school students for athletic events. Subsequent posts will show how the school district will be utilizing capital outlay funds rather than attempting another bond issue. You'll see in the last sentence of the article, the mill rate will increase by just under 1 mill for this plan. For most households in Coffeyville, this will be an increase of less than $12 a year! More info on mill rates (for those interested) to come!

As many of you know, the school district is working on reopening schools. We will be offering two models this year. The first is ON-SITE learning, this is school as we all know it but with extra safety precautions put in place. The second is REMOTE learning from home. Online enrollment should begin Monday, August 3rd. Please check back here for more information regarding the reopening of schools and what it will look like for your student.

DON'T FORGET!!!

â€¼ï¸Technology and School Belonging Drop Offâ€¼ï¸

3rd-12th Grade Students
Technology equipment turn in for students will be Monday the 18th 11 am to 1 pm and 4 pm to 6 pm and Tuesday the 19th 11 am to 1 pm and 4 pm to 6 pm at the Field Kindley Technical Academy. Enter off of 6th Street, pull into the parking lot, and wait for an attendant to come to your car. Have the laptop turned on for inspection of the condition. You will be asked to sign off on the return sheet. Please don't forget the power adapter.

7th-12th Grade Students
You will also need to turn in your packets, sports equipment, and anything else that belongs to the school at this time also. There will be a building rep for you to drop these items off with.

You will drop your technology equipment off first then pull forward and drop off your other belongings to the appropriate school building staff member.

K-6th Grade Students
DON'T FORGET!!! a separate time for you to turn in your books.

In response to #COVID19, families with children who received free or reduced meals this last school year will receive up to $291 per child to purchase food.

How to receive pandemic EBT:
ğŸ‘‰ Families with children who participate in programs including SNAP food assistance, child care assistance, or TANF cash assistance: The one-time benefit will be automatically loaded onto your EBT card in the next few weeks
ğŸ‘‰ If your family doesn't participate in SNAP, child care assistance, or TANF, but you do have kids participating in free/reduced lunch, you will be mailed a pre-loaded card in the next few weeks.

shared_text:
Randy Watson
March 15 at 4:33 PM Â·

As of Sunday, March 15, Kansas Education Commissioner Dr. Randy Watson strongly recommends that those schools currently coming off of spring break, suspend operations for the week March 16-20. All schools scheduled for spring break the week of March 16-20 will continue as planned. For schools who have spring break later in time, Commissioner Watson is strongly recommending they also close schools for the period of March 16-20.

Closing all schools during this same period of time provides Kansas officials the time needed to finalize a comprehensive plan for how to address COVID-19.

It is critical that we all follow a coordinated response to this situation.

Community Elementary School of Coffeyville
March 3 at 8:50 PM Â·

Mr. Jim Porter, Kansas State Board of Education member for District 9, was a guest speaker today for 3rd grade students. Mr. Porter provided a valuable state link to a governmental entity as part of a recent service learning project. Students were able to share their knowledge of what it takes to be good citizens, different legislative/governmental offices, and the election process. Mr. Porter shared aspects of his role on the state school board and told the students that his favorite part was being able to speak to students and make a difference in their lives. Thank you Mr. Porter for visiting CES and answering our burning questions. We appreciate you!

COME ONE COME ALL!!!! It's Dodgeball time! Come out and support a great event!

RMS is having its 3rd annual dodgeball tournament this Saturday, November 16th at 4:00 pm in the FKHS gym. We are taking late registrations!!!!!! You can bring form and money on Saturday but please contact Steve Becker or Mona Gayle Voss if interested in adding a team. Anyone 11 years of age and older is welcome to participate, 5 players per team and $25 a team.

And if you are not interested in playing please come out and support...there will be an awesome concession stand with pulled pork sandwiches or nachos, pizza and of course candy and pop. Admission fee is $1 for students and $2 for adults.
